english:
  title: Memorial of Gratitude for the Imperial Letter, Robes, and State Dispatches
  author: Choi Chi-won
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Your servant humbly submits this memorial.

    On the twenty-sixth day of the second month, the Imperial Envoy Yi Jong-baek arrived, and your servant has been graced with the benevolence of His Majesty. You have bestowed upon me separately an imperial letter, court robes trimmed at the collar, a dragon's-breath incense, golden vessels and ornaments, a silver-gilt flower-scattered bowl, and a silver flask with golden flowers.

    In each character of the royal script, I perceive the divine hand. The grace clings to the imperial garments like morning dew. The fragrance of celestial perfume seeps into the very root of my nose, while the radiance of these precious vessels leaps forth before my eyes. I am immersed in this singular honor, yet cannot help but tremble with anxiety. Truly am I moved; truly am I humbled. I bow my head in gratitude, again and again.

    Your servant has long harbored the thought that, having inherited the arts of archery and horsemanship from my ancestors and unworthy as I am to hold the symbols of command, I am sworn to pour forth all loyalty and ultimately repay the benevolence of the royal court. Last year I personally led brave soldiers, desiring to vanquish the treacherous foe. Yet soon came your imperial directive, and already my naval forces have been stationed in their posts. Though I am ashamed of my empty oaths at the helm, I harbor yet the earnest hope to gird my loins for battle. But now, unexpectedly, the imperial messenger has delivered the celestial command, and the sovereign's own brush has inscribed words exceeding even Confucius's single word of praise—nay, surpassing even Emperor Guangwu's ten-line edicts of commendation.

    Moreover, you have deigned to portion out treasures from the royal treasury, filling the fragrant chamber with perfume. Flowers are delicately carved into precious metal of Li-water, and vessels clear as snow from Ren-mountain are presented before me. As I hold and examine these gifts, the very officials marvel, and as I place them in sealed cases for preservation, they shall illuminate my descendants through endless ages.

    Though I have been fortunate enough to encounter this glorious age, and honors have gathered upon one unworthy frame, I receive reward without merit, and shame fills my heart with no place to hide. I am merely the recipient of vast imperial grace—how can I display the cunning of the leopard? My body dwells by Chu's waters, yet I have not submitted the report of victory; my gaze reaches toward Shu's distant sky, and I can only weep tears of gratitude.

    Your servant is confined to the administration of the frontier garrison and cannot travel to the imperial court to offer proper thanks in person. I am overwhelmed with conflicting emotions of joy and trepidation beyond measure. I respectfully attach this memorial of gratitude, to be conveyed by the Imperial Attendant Yi Jong-baek upon his return, submitting it humbly for the royal ear.
  footnotes:
    - Choi Chi-won (최치원, 846-?) was a celebrated Silla scholar-official and one of Korea's greatest classical poets. This memorial is written in the formal diplomatic style required for high-ranking officials addressing the throne.
    - The references to 'divine hand' (神筆), 'celestial perfume' (仙香), and classical allusions to Confucius and Emperor Guangwu employ traditional Chinese literary conventions to express reverence while maintaining the dignity appropriate to a frontier commander.
    - The geographical references to Chu-water and Shu-sky are classical allusions suggesting distance and longing—the writer expresses regret at being unable to present victories in person due to his remote posting.
